definition.value: The offspring of one's spouse, but not one's own offspring, neither biological nor through adoption.
A partner in marriage.
A person who is not one's biological sibling, but was legally and socially raised as if they were.
A sibling through being in foster care of the same parent or parents.
A sibling, usually either biological or adoptive, who is legally considered as such.
The child of one's stepparent from another relationship.
A person with whom someone has had sex; a sex partner.
A person who is the partner of a bisexual person.
A person who is the partner of a gay person.
The romantic and/or sexual partner of a transgender person.
The romantic and/or sexual partner of a cisgender person.
A person who is the partner of a heterosexual person.
A person whose partner is a transmasculine person.
A person whose partner is a transfeminine person.
A person whose partner is a nonbinary person.
A person whose partner is a transgender woman.
A person whose partner is a transgender man.
A person who has adopted a child, as opposed to a biological parent or parents.
A person from whom a child inherits one half of their DNA.
An adult who cares for a child who has been placed in foster care.
A parent, usually either biological or adoptive, who is legally considered as such.
A parent who is the only guardian of offspring.

A person who provides biological material (egg and/or sperm), but not necessarily genetic material, or otherwise assists in the creation of a child (such as carrying the pregnancy to term for an egg/sperm combo that is not their own).
A romantic partner for life. This can be same-sex or opposite-sex, married or without marriage, and monogamous or polyamorous.
A partner who is asexual.
A partner through non-marital means or to whom one is not married.
Relatives unrelated by birth and/or marriage, but with which one has an emotionally significant relationship similar to that of a family relationship.
An adult person who is transfeminine, usually a transgender woman.
A social behavior that benefits other people or society as a whole, such as helping, sharing, donating, co-operating, and volunteering.

A disorder diagnosed in childhood or adolescence age group characterized by aggressive behavior, deceitfulness, destruction of property or violation of rules that is persistent and repetitive, and within a one year period.
Conduct disorder characterized by persistent dissocial or aggressive behavior.

A classification of disorders in the Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders (DSM) that are usually diagnosed in infancy, childhood or adolescence and are characterized by an individual's inability to behave in a cooperative manner.
Someone who advocates for human rights.
Someone who advocates for minority rights.
Someone who advocates for LGBTQIA+ rights.
Someone who advocates for gay rights.
Someone who advocates for bisexual rights.
Someone who advocates for transgender rights.
Someone who advocates for intersex rights.
A person of a dominant or privileged racial, gender, sexual or other identity who support and seek to further the causes of those who lack such privilege (such as people of color or LGBTQ people).
A straight ally or heterosexual ally is a heterosexual person who supports equal civil rights, gender equality, LGBTQ social movements, and challenges homophobia, biphobia and transphobia.
One who advocates for LGBTQIA+ people.
A person who advocates for protection of the natural environment.
Someone who advocates for sex workers' rights.
Someone who advocates for women's rights.
A person who promotes suffrage.
Persons who utilize the internet in order to support any of various forms of activism.
Persons who advocate for any of various political changes and/or reforms.
A patterned network of relationships constituting a coherent whole that exist between individuals, groups, and institutions.
Social structures that establish the number of genders and their associated gender roles in society.
